{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626082"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:33:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:33:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17057"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17057"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.41,0.11,0.11,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9747"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77006"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9747"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17057"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62512"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5295"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23096"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77006"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlucocorticoids are commonly prescribed anti-inflammatory and immunosuppressive medications that act through specific intracellular pathways.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of glucocorticoids?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks leucocyte adhesion to endothelium","Binds cytoplasmic receptors and suppresses gene transcription","Stabilises inflammatory cell membranes","Binds nuclear receptors to activate anti-inflammatory genes","Degrades pro-inflammatory cytokines"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGlucocorticoids primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding cytoplasmic receptors and suppressing gene transcription\u003C/strong\u003E. After binding, the receptor-glucocorticoid complex moves to the nucleus where it acts as a transcription factor to suppress inflammatory gene expression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks leucocyte adhesion to endothelium\u003C/strong\u003E is a downstream effect that occurs due to reduced inflammatory mediator production, not the primary mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStabilises inflammatory cell membranes\u003C/strong\u003E may occur secondarily but is not the main mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinds nuclear receptors to activate anti-inflammatory genes\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as glucocorticoids must first bind to cytoplasmic receptors before nuclear translocation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDegrades pro-inflammatory cytokines\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as glucocorticoids reduce cytokine production through gene suppression rather than direct degradation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe suppression of inflammatory gene transcription leads to reduced production of cytokines, adhesion molecules, and other inflammatory mediators, resulting in broad anti-inflammatory effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Glucocorticoids suppress immune responses by inhibiting transcription of pro-inflammatory genes.","Glucocorticoids bind to cytoplasmic receptors which then translocate to the nucleus.","Nuclear glucocorticoid receptors act as transcription factors to regulate gene expression."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62512"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17057"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62512"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:16:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9747"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77006"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nul